<P STYLE="margin-top: 0.85cm; margin-bottom: 0cm; line-height: 100%; page-break-inside: avoid; page-break-after: avoid"><A NAME="__RefHeading__4998_607494244"></A>
<FONT FACE="Times New Roman, serif"><FONT SIZE=3><U><B>2Procedures</B></U></FONT></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top: 0.64cm; margin-bottom: 0cm; line-height: 100%; page-break-inside: avoid; page-break-after: avoid"><A NAME="__RefHeading__5000_607494244"></A>
<FONT FACE="Times New Roman, serif"><FONT SIZE=3><B>2.1CCD handling
(ESD and contamination)</B></FONT></FONT></P>
<P ALIGN=JUSTIFY STYLE="margin-top: 0.21cm; line-height: 100%"><FONT FACE="Times New Roman, serif"><FONT SIZE=3>Contamination
and electrostatic discharge control protocols are described in detail
in [4] and [5] To prevent a potentially damaging signal reaching the
CCD, is also critical to check, using appropriate test equipment,
that the CCD clock and bias signals are all present on the correct
pins of the cables that connect to the CCD. In general this check
only needs to be done when there has been a change to the controller
hardware or software.</FONT></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top: 0.64cm; margin-bottom: 0cm; line-height: 100%; page-break-inside: avoid; page-break-after: avoid"><A NAME="__RefHeading__5002_607494244"></A>
<FONT FACE="Times New Roman, serif"><FONT SIZE=3><B>2.2Readout System
Initialization</B></FONT></FONT></P>
<P ALIGN=JUSTIFY STYLE="margin-top: 0.21cm; line-height: 100%"><FONT FACE="Times New Roman, serif"><FONT SIZE=3>After
the CCD is installed and the controller signals have been verified,
shorting plugs are removed and the CCD is connected to the
controller. The controller is then powered up and a
version-controlled configuration file is loaded. When the
configuration parameters are APPLIED the system enters a state in
which the clocks and biases are isolated from the CCD by
opto-isolated solid-state relays. The controller is then commanded to
enter the POWER-ON state, whereby the bias and clock signals are
enabled in the appropriate sequence. The DC bias currents are then
checked (with clocks not running); any current which is outside its
allowed limits is an indication of a poor connection or, possibly, a
bad device. The next step is to activate the clocks and take a test
image, with the CCD in the dark. Operators need to be trained to
identify the proper appearance of a room-temperature CCD image. After
these checks are complete, the controller should be set back to the
POWERDOWN state and cryostat pumping and cooldown can be initiated..</FONT></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top: 0.64cm; margin-bottom: 0cm; line-height: 100%; page-break-inside: avoid; page-break-after: avoid"><A NAME="__RefHeading__5004_607494244"></A>
<FONT FACE="Times New Roman, serif"><FONT SIZE=3><B>2.3Cryostat
operation</B></FONT></FONT></P>
<P ALIGN=JUSTIFY STYLE="margin-top: 0.21cm; line-height: 100%"><FONT FACE="Times New Roman, serif"><FONT SIZE=3>After
loading a new device into the cryostat and performing the readout
system initialization, the Dewar window is installed and the backing
vacuum pump is started. If conditions warrant, the Dewar is purged
with dry nitrogen gas (5X fill and evacuate). Rough pumping should
proceed until the foreline pressure is below 5 mtorr, at which point
the turbomolecular pump is started. Pumping should proceed until the
chamber pressure reaches 5x10<SUP>-5</SUP> torr, when liquid nitrogen
transfer can be started. Experience with the R&amp;D Dewars at BNL
and Harvard indicates that the cooldown rate will not exceed the
manufacturer’s recommended maximum; but if necessary, the
temperature controller can be set to limit the temperature rate of
change. When LN2 fill is complete, the temperature controller control
loop is enabled with setpoint at -95C and the vacuum valve is closed.
Testing can begin when the temperature becomes stable at -95C.</FONT></FONT></P>
<P ALIGN=JUSTIFY STYLE="margin-top: 0.21cm; line-height: 100%"><FONT FACE="Times New Roman, serif"><FONT SIZE=3>After
the conclusion of testing, the controller is set to the POWERDOWN
state. Depending on the remaining LN2 level the Dewar is either
allowed to warm up naturally or the temperature controller is
commanded to apply successively increasing setpoints to raise the
temperature in a controlled fashion. When the Dewar internal
temperatures have reached a point where there is no danger of
condensation, the Dewar pressure is brought up to 760torr with dry N2
gas. The window flange can then be opened and the CCD exchanged.</FONT></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top: 0.64cm; margin-bottom: 0cm; line-height: 100%; page-break-inside: avoid; page-break-after: avoid"><A NAME="__RefHeading__5006_607494244"></A>
<FONT FACE="Times New Roman, serif"><FONT SIZE=3><B>2.4Scripted
Acquisition</B></FONT></FONT></P>
<P ALIGN=JUSTIFY STYLE="margin-top: 0.21cm; line-height: 100%"><FONT FACE="Times New Roman, serif"><FONT SIZE=3>In
production, the eTraveler and Job Harness software (see eTraveler
User’s Manual, available at
<FONT COLOR="#0000ff"><U><A CLASS="western" HREF="https://confluence.slac.stanford.edu/display/LSSTCAM/eTraveler+Definition+-+User%27s+Manual">https://confluence.slac.stanford.edu/display/LSSTCAM/eTraveler+Definition+-+User%27s+Manual</A></U></FONT>
) will coordinate the running of all test and assembly operations
including EO testing. TS3 will be able to acquire all datasets needed
for full CCD characterization without operator intervention. The
Python scripting language will be used to define the image and
metadata acquisition and produce the data products described in [1].
Subsequent image analysis software will run (on the DAQ computer in
the cleanroom) and generate the final performance report. </FONT></FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="margin-top: 0.64cm; margin-bottom: 0cm; line-height: 100%; page-break-inside: avoid; page-break-after: avoid"><A NAME="__RefHeading__5008_607494244"></A>
<FONT FACE="Times New Roman, serif"><FONT SIZE=3><B>2.5Calibrations</B></FONT></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top: 0.42cm; margin-bottom: 0cm; line-height: 100%; page-break-inside: avoid; page-break-after: avoid"><A NAME="__RefHeading__5010_607494244"></A>
<FONT SIZE=3><U>2.5.1Working photodiode absolute response as a
function of wavelength.</U></FONT></P>
<P ALIGN=JUSTIFY STYLE="margin-top: 0.21cm; line-height: 100%"><FONT FACE="Times New Roman, serif"><FONT SIZE=3>LCA-10103
par. 9.8.3 refers to a “QE system calibration file”. Working
photodiodes are used for measuring the light flux in the integrating
sphere during QE measurements. They are calibrated to provide
information about the absolute irradiance at the location of the
sensor in the cryostat during QE testing at Test Stands 3 and 8. </FONT></FONT>
</P>
<P ALIGN=JUSTIFY STYLE="margin-top: 0.21cm; line-height: 100%"><FONT FACE="Times New Roman, serif"><FONT SIZE=3><U>Calibration
process</U> – A secondary standard photodiode with a calibrated
aperture and a known response function (amps/watt vs.wavelength) is
placed at the location of the sensor plane. The current measured by
this PD gives the absolute irradiance at the sensor plane. A window
of the same thickness and with the same optical properties as that
used on the cryostat is placed at the proper distance away from the
standard PD. Baffles are inserted between the IS aperture and the PD
in the same configuration as used in the actual sensor QE
measurement. The working PD is mounted in a specific port on the
integrating sphere. It monitors the light intensity inside the
integrating sphere. Currents from each PD are measured with the
Kiethley picoammeters (after adjusting for dark current). The
monochromator slits are set at the proper width and the monochromator
is scanned through a series of discrete wavelengths with the shutter
open. Current from both PDs is recorded as a function of wavelength.
The secondary standard current is converted into photon flux using
its calibration curve and this photon flux value is used to calibrate
the output of the working PD. The result is a response table that
converts working PD current into absolute photon flux at the sensor
plane as a function of wavelength. </FONT></FONT>
</P>
<P ALIGN=JUSTIFY STYLE="margin-top: 0.21cm; line-height: 100%"><FONT FACE="Times New Roman, serif"><FONT SIZE=3><U>Calibration
verification</U> – Recalibration of the working photodiodes is done
periodically to generate updated response curves. Secondary standards
are maintained in a controlled environment to prevent degradation
during storage. Records are maintained in the eLog system.</FONT></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top: 0.42cm; margin-bottom: 0cm; line-height: 100%; page-break-inside: avoid; page-break-after: avoid"><A NAME="__RefHeading__5012_607494244"></A>
<FONT SIZE=3><U>2.5.2Recertification of secondary transfer standard
photodiodes.</U></FONT></P>
<P ALIGN=JUSTIFY STYLE="margin-top: 0.21cm; line-height: 100%"><FONT FACE="Times New Roman, serif"><FONT SIZE=3>Secondary
photodiode standards are sent out to an accredited calibration
laboratory on a yearly basis for recalibration and recertification.
The diodes will be equipped with an aperture mask that defines the
active area and is permanently attached. The area of the mask will be
measured with the OGP vision probe to define the precise area exposed
to the photon flux. This is necessary because the response of the
photodiode varies with position across its surface. Unless a
well-defined area is selected by a mask each time it is used, the
response of the PD will differ between measurements. Records are
maintained in the eLog system.</FONT></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top: 0.42cm; margin-bottom: 0cm; line-height: 100%; page-break-inside: avoid; page-break-after: avoid"><A NAME="__RefHeading__5014_607494244"></A>
<FONT SIZE=3><U>2.5.3Uniformity of illumination at sensor position in
cryostat.</U></FONT></P>
<P ALIGN=JUSTIFY STYLE="margin-top: 0.21cm; line-height: 100%"><FONT FACE="Times New Roman, serif"><FONT SIZE=3>Relative
uniformity of the photon irradiance from the integrating sphere in
the sensor plane will be measured by scanning a PD across the active
area of the sensor and raft in Test Stands 3 and 8. Precautions will
need to be taken to avoid extraneous light from impinging upon the PD
during the measurement. The scanning system needs to be well-shielded
from room lights and other potential error sources. Dark scans will
be done to ensure that conditions are stable and low level light
contamination is uniform and time invariant. This measurement will be
done at a number of wavelengths to measure the field uniformity as a
function of wavelength.</FONT></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top: 0.42cm; margin-bottom: 0cm; line-height: 100%; page-break-inside: avoid; page-break-after: avoid"><A NAME="__RefHeading__5016_607494244"></A>
<FONT SIZE=3><U>2.5.4Monochromator wavelength settings.</U></FONT></P>
<P ALIGN=JUSTIFY STYLE="margin-top: 0.21cm; line-height: 100%"><FONT FACE="Times New Roman, serif"><FONT SIZE=3>The
monochromator wavelength settings will be calibrated by using
spectral source lamps with well-defined wavelengths throughout the
near UV, visible, and near IR regions. Low pressure Hg PenRay lamps
are used. Wavelength accuracy for the Cornerstone 260 monochromator
is specified to be 0.35 nm. This accuracy is more than adequate for
QE calibration. The use of a calibration file will probably not be
necessary.</FONT></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top: 0.42cm; margin-bottom: 0cm; line-height: 100%; page-break-inside: avoid; page-break-after: avoid"><A NAME="__RefHeading__5018_607494244"></A>
<FONT SIZE=3><U>2.5.5Bandpass filter passband.</U></FONT></P>
<P ALIGN=JUSTIFY STYLE="margin-top: 0.21cm; line-height: 100%"><FONT FACE="Times New Roman, serif"><FONT SIZE=3>Filters
used to define specific wavelength bands generally come from the
vendor with a plot of the measured passband. In many cases, only the
catalog information is available for the nominal filter. When
necessary, filters will be measured for transmission characteristics
by using the monochromator as the wavelength selector and measuring
the transmission of the filter places at the output of the
monochromator, immediately in front of a photodiode detector. Only
relative transmission is important, so the recorded signal can be
normalized to the maximum transmission. </FONT></FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="margin-top: 0.42cm; margin-bottom: 0cm; line-height: 100%; page-break-inside: avoid; page-break-after: avoid"><A NAME="__RefHeading__5020_607494244"></A>
<FONT SIZE=3><U>2.5.6Out-of-band transmission of bandpass and
order-sorting filters.</U></FONT></P>
<P ALIGN=JUSTIFY STYLE="margin-top: 0.21cm; line-height: 100%"><FONT FACE="Times New Roman, serif"><FONT SIZE=3>Bandpass
filters and order-sorting high-pass cut-on filters are designed to
minimize out-of-band transmission. It will be necessary to measure
the order-sorting filters used in front of the monochromator for
transmission at wavelengths below the cut-on wavelength. This is
especially important when strong lines at shorter wavelengths may
show up in second order when the monochromator is at twice their
wavelengths. The same measurement method can be used as for bandpass
filters.</FONT></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top: 0.42cm; margin-bottom: 0cm; line-height: 100%; page-break-inside: avoid; page-break-after: avoid"><A NAME="__RefHeading__5022_607494244"></A>
<FONT SIZE=3><U>2.5.7Calibration of picoammeters and voltage sources.</U></FONT></P>
<P ALIGN=JUSTIFY STYLE="margin-top: 0.21cm; line-height: 100%"><FONT FACE="Times New Roman, serif"><FONT SIZE=3>Keithley
picoammeters and voltage sources will be sent out to a certified
calibration laboratory on a regular schedule for recalibration.
Calibration certificates will be maintained on eLog.</FONT></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top: 0.42cm; margin-bottom: 0cm; line-height: 100%; page-break-inside: avoid; page-break-after: avoid"><A NAME="__RefHeading__5024_607494244"></A>
<FONT SIZE=3><U>2.5.8Cross-calibration of test station equipment at
BNL and at Paris.</U></FONT></P>
<P ALIGN=JUSTIFY STYLE="margin-top: 0.21cm; line-height: 100%"><FONT FACE="Times New Roman, serif"><FONT SIZE=3>Some
fraction of the sensors will undergo QE testing at Paris before they
are sent to BNL for assembly into the RSA. One or more sensors will
be tested by both laboratories to insure that our measurements agree.
This will be done periodically to insure that there is no divergence
in results between laboratories.</FONT></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top: 0.42cm; margin-bottom: 0cm; line-height: 100%; page-break-inside: avoid; page-break-after: avoid"><A NAME="__RefHeading__5026_607494244"></A>
<FONT SIZE=3><U>2.5.9Shutter speed calibration for exposures.</U></FONT></P>
<P ALIGN=JUSTIFY STYLE="margin-top: 0.21cm; line-height: 100%"><FONT FACE="Times New Roman, serif"><FONT SIZE=3>The
monochromator has an internal fast shutter that can be actuated at a
40 Hz repetition rate with a minimum exposure open time of 2 msec.
Since minimum exposure duration will be set at 0.5 s, it should not
be necessary to calibrate the open/close dynamics of the shutter.
Actual performance can be measured by capturing signals from a fast
photodiode synchronized to the TTL actuation pulse. </FONT></FONT>
</P>
<P ALIGN=JUSTIFY STYLE="margin-top: 0.21cm; line-height: 100%; page-break-before: always">
<BR><BR>
</P>
